data.title: Hop Power Players: Billboard’s 2023 List of Executives Revealed
data.meta_description: Billboard's 2023 R&B/Hip-Hop Power Players list — honoring the executives setting the bar throughout the genres — is led by gamma founder Larry Jackson.
data.text:
Larry Jackson

Founder, gamma

In February, TikTok’s 1 billion-plus users received an unexpected gift for Valentine’s Day: exclusive access to the catalog of one of hip-hop’s most revered labels, Death Row Records. Snoop Dogg had purchased the catalog in 2022 and pulled it from streaming services. So the only place to hear tracks from Snoop’s classic Doggystyle or 2Pac’s 10-times-platinum All Eyez on Me was TikTok.

This partnership — as unusual as it was savvy — was the handiwork of veteran music executive Larry Jackson, 42, who seized the attention of the industry this year when he launched his entertainment company, gamma. Backed by $1 billion in financing and focused on putting that capital to work “in particular and acutely on Black culture,” Jackson has created a deep-pocketed alternative to the major labels.

Read Billboard ’s full profile on executive of the year Larry Jackson here.

She’yaa “21 Savage” Abraham-Joseph

Justin “Meezy” Williams

Co-founders, Slaughter Gang Entertainment

Williams, who began managing 21 Savage in 2015, heads up Slaughter Gang Entertainment, the label he co-founded with the Billboard Hot 100-topping rapper. A highlight of the past year, he says, has been “building our new artists” and seeing those who have begun to make waves get bigger, including 21 Lil Harold, Yung Sinn, SG Tip, Big Bratt and Kid Hazel. Williams is also proud of the company’s work “executive-producing and co-distributing the Freaknik soundtrack for the Hulu documentary,” an album that accompanies the movie about students from historically Black colleges and universities attending Atlanta’s annual spring break party.

Tunji Balogun

Chairman/CEO, Def Jam Recordings

LaTrice Burnette

Executive vp, Def Jam Recordings; president, 4th & Broadway

Archie Davis

Executive vp/chief creative officer, Def Jam Recordings

Natina Nimene

Executive vp of promotion and artist relations, Def Jam Recordings

Naim McNair

Noah Preston

Executive vps of A&R, Def Jam Recordings

“Our journey over the last 18 months has been about establishing this company as an agile, insightful and powerful engine for artist development,” says Balogun. The label chief goes on to cite recent Grammy Award winner Muni Long; Coco Jones and her first Mainstream R&B/Hip-Hop Airplay No. 1, “ICU”; and rising rapper Armani White. “Together with the bold A&R work and development around artists like Fridayy, Adekunle Gold and Chase Shakur, these artists represent a super diverse cross-section of the culture,” he adds, “and are the future lifeblood of Def Jam.”

Katina Bynum

Executive vp of East Coast labels for urban, Universal Music Enterprises

Bynum captures a professional highlight of the past year in one word: “Rihanna.” The singer’s headlining performance at the Super Bowl LVII halftime show in February was preceded by the 2022 release of the Black Panther: Wakanda Forever soundtrack, which featured Rihanna’s latest song, “Lift Me Up.” The album reached No. 1 on the Soundtracks chart. Following the Super Bowl performance, “Rihanna’s overall catalog received a huge boost [both in] audio and video streams,” says Bynum, pushing “her total streams to an all-time high.”

Juan “DJ Kast One” Cabral

Associate director of A&R, Legacy Recordings

Cabral has built a solid rep spinning hip-hop, R&B and reggae as DJ Kast One at WQHT (Hot 97) New York, “where hip-hop lives,” as the station’s slogan goes. As associate director of A&R at Legacy Recordings, the Bronx native works with content, marketing and digital teams to identify trends and elevate “music that can help refresh and revitalize catalog assets,” he says. For example, he assigned and oversaw mixings for Miguel’s “Sure Thing” and Ruth B’s “Dandelions” and applied Dolby’s Atmos spacial audio technology to Run-D.M.C.’s catalog albums and Khalid’s American Teen for its fifth-anniversary campaign.

Don Cannon

Leighton “Lake” Morrison

Tyree “DJ Drama” Simmons

Co-founders, Generation Now

Generation Now enjoyed another fruitful year courtesy of stars Lil Uzi Vert and Jack Harlow. In February, Uzi scored his seventh top 10 on the Hot 100 with his Jersey club hit, “Just Wanna Rock,” which also reached No. 1 on the Hot Rap Songs chart after its adoption as an anthem for the Philadelphia Eagles’ Super Bowl run. Harlow netted his third top 10 on the Billboard 200 and first No. 1 on Top Rap Albums with Jackman. He also evolved into a TV darling, starring in the modern-day remake of the 1990s cult classic White Men Can’t Jump and appearing in Lil Dicky’s FX comedy series, DAVE. “This year, we took Generation Now to a whole new level,” says Morrison. “We are most proud of all our work in Atlanta to better the community and empower the youth while continuing to push the culture forward and create opportunity.”

Steve “Steve O” Carless

President of A&R, Warner Records

Dionnee Harper

Executive vp of marketing and artist development, Warner Records

Ericka Coulter

Senior vp of A&R, Warner Records

Ron Stewart

Senior vp of urban promotion, Warner Records

Warner Records found a rising hip-hop star this year in signee NLE Choppa, who notched two gold singles with “Slut Me Out” and his 2 Rare collaboration “Do It Again.” In addition, the Memphis rapper achieved success on both radio and the road, landing two top 10 singles this year on both the Mainstream R&B/Hip-Hop Airplay and Rhythmic Airplay charts and making over 30 high school and college visits across the country. In June, Choppa was a featured artist at the WHTA (Hot 107.9) Birthday Bash in Atlanta.

Bill Evans

Executive vp of urban promotion, Capitol Music Group

Orlando Wharton

Executive vp, Capitol Music Group

Twin Clark

Senior vp of artist relations, Motown

Kenoe Jordan

Vp of A&R, Motown

Jessica Eason

Vp of marketing, Capitol Music Group

Dante Smith

Vp of digital marketing, Capitol Music Group

R&B and hip-hop flourished as genres at Capitol Music Group and Motown over the past year with breakthroughs from rising stars like Doechii and Toosii as well as Ice Spice, who landed four tracks in the Hot 100 top 10. “We have incredibly talented artists in the pipeline,” says Wharton, “and Capitol Music Group will continue to prove to the world that we are a real force in these genres.”

Kendell “Sav” Freeman

Vp/co-head of urban music, Arista Records

Khris Riddick-Tynes

Vp of A&R/co-head of urban music, Arista Records; president, producer, songwriter, Sam Edmonds Songs

For Freeman and Riddick-Tynes, the success of the past year has been largely defined by Arista’s newest slate of artists. Along with the continued rise of acts like Idman and Audrey Nuna, they both emphasize the introduction of Lola Brooke as a major highlight of 2023, thanks to her breakout success with “Don’t Play With It,” the burgeoning rapper’s first Hot 100 entry. Says Freeman: “Seeing all the adoration and critical acclaim Lola has received from fans, peers and critics as well as the worldwide success she has achieved so far has been an exciting experience.”

Lanre Gaba

Michael Kyser

Co-presidents of Black music, Atlantic Records

Marsha St. Hubert

Senior vp/head of marketing, Atlantic Records

Success Davis

Vp of A&R, Atlantic Records

Shauna James

Senior manager of Black music digital marketing, Atlantic Records

Atlantic’s deep-rooted commitment to artist development has continued to pay off. On the heels of recent success with projects from Burna Boy (“Last Last”), Kodak Black (“Super Gremlin”) and Ravyn Lenae (“Skin Tight,” her first No. 1 on Adult R&B Airplay, featuring Steve Lacy), the label dialed up attention with Kali’s “Area Codes.” Signed to Atlantic during the pandemic, the rap newcomer achieved her first Hot 100 hit with the TikTok-driven track, which peaked at No. 33. “With the success of ‘Area Codes,’ ” says Gaba, “we are incredibly excited about breaking yet another new artist.”

Ghazi

Founder/CEO, EMPIRE

Nima Etminan

COO, EMPIRE

Tina Davis

President, EMPIRE

Eamon Mulligan

Senior vp of product and ecommerce, EMPIRE

Harrison Golding

Vp of strategic marketing, EMPIRE

EMPIRE’s standing as a champion of its hometown Bay Area hip-hop scene was bolstered once again by the release of The Great Escape from Larry June and The Alchemist, which reached No. 32 on the Billboard 200 and prefaced a 60-city North American headline tour that Etminan calls “a great example of an independent artist carving out their own lane.” Detroit MC Peezy also reached a career best with the single “2 Million Up,” which earned a BET Award nomination and an RIAA gold certification.

Yo Gotti

Founder/CEO, Collective Music Group

The Tennessee rapper and label executive’s imprint enjoyed a big year, with new signee GloRilla establishing herself as a hot new artist. Named to XXL’s 2023 Freshman Class after scoring Hot 100 hits with “F.N.F. (Let’s Go)” (with Hitkidd) and “Tomorrow 2” (with Cardi B), she and fellow CMG artist Moneybagg Yo recently hit the chart with “On Wat U On.” Meanwhile, their labelmates 42 Dugg, EST Gee, Blac Youngsta, Mozzy and R&B singer Lehla Samia continued to build careers. “Everyone on the team plays a part in the win,” Gotti told Billboard in 2022. “That’s why it’s called Collective Music Group.”

Elliot Grainge

Founder/CEO, 10K Projects

Zach Friedman

Tony Talamo

Co-presidents, 10K Projects

“Hip-hop remains the foundation of everything we’ve built at 10K over these past few years,” says Grainge, who applauds Trippie Redd’s ability to “push the creative envelope with his amazing work,” including his latest album, Mansion Musik, which peaked at No. 3 on the Billboard 200. Meanwhile, hot new signee Ice Spice “has emerged as one of the biggest artists of the year,” Grainge adds, with four top 10 hits on the Hot 100, including the No. 7 debut of “Barbie World” (see story, page 60).

Naji Grampus

Vp of streaming and strategy, The Orchard

Grampus recently entered a new partnership between The Orchard and his own label, 24/8 Music Group. The joint venture is dedicated to developing hip-hop and R&B artists and “reinforces The Orchard’s mission to be a true home for creators,” Grampus says. The Orchard also signed Diddy’s Love Records and led release strategies for Nas’ King’s Disease III — which debuted at No. 10 in November on the Billboard 200, tying Nas with Jay-Z for the most top 10 albums on the chart by a rapper — and Lojay’s “Monalisa” (with Sarz and Chris Brown), which reached No. 8 on the U.S. Afrobeats Songs chart. “We have seen tremendous success,” Grampus says, “with Human Re Sources’ breakout artist RAYE and DJ Premier’s Hip Hop Volume 1 in partnership with Mass Appeal as well as Stomp Down Records’ Houston-born rapper Monaleo.”

Saint Harraway

Executive vp of A&R, Republic Records; co-president, Uptown Records

Mike Horton

Executive vp of promotion, Republic Records

Danielle Price

Executive vp, Republic Records

Ken “Duro” Ifill

Senior vp of A&R, Republic Records; operations manager, NYC Republic -Recording Studio

Dave Ingenloff

Senior vp of rhythm cross promotion, Republic Records

Xiarra Diamond Nimrod

Vp of marketing strategy, Republic Records

The relaunch of iconic label Uptown Records underscores Republic’s commitment to R&B/hip-hop music and culture. “The Uptown team, led by Harraway and [fellow co-president] Marleny Reyes, has done a phenomenal job at this early stage building and supporting a roster of incredible artists who speak to the legacy of the label, yet represent the future of our business,” says Price. Republic is also home to The Weeknd, Drake, Nicki Minaj, newly minted Songwriters Hall of Fame honoree Post Malone and up-and-comer Coi Leray, as well as hip-hop producer ATL Jacob and his Wicked Money Family label.

Kevin Liles

Chairman/CEO, 300 Elektra Entertainment

Rayna Bass

Selim Bouab

Co-presidents, 300 Entertainment

Leesa Brunson-Boland

Senior vp/head of A&R operations and administration, 300 Entertainment

Lallie Jones

Vp of marketing, 300 Entertainment

Michael McArthur

Vp of A&R, 300 Entertainment

300 Entertainment remains a significant force in hip-hop with artists like Megan Thee Stallion, Gunna and Young Thug. Despite its rap-heavy roster, the label also scored big in R&B when Mary J. Blige notched six Grammy Award nominations for this year’s ceremony, including an album of the year nod. Younger stars flourish, notably PinkPantheress, who scored her first Hot 100 top five song alongside Ice Spice with their “Boy’s a Liar, Pt. 2” collaboration. 300 has also built out other divisions, including 300 Publishing, Sparta and 300 Studios, which recently won a sports Emmy Award for its debut project, Race. 300 Entertainment co-presidents Bass and Bouab both say that the past year shows the label can operate at a high level in multiple aspects of the business.

Chioke “Stretch” McCoy

Co-founder/managing partner/president, Blac Noize! Recordings

Charley Greenberg

Co-founder/managing partner/GM, Blac Noize! Recordings

Tony Bucher

Co-founder/managing partner/COO, Blac Noize! Recordings

“Nimble” was the key word for Blac Noize! Recordings in 2022, says McCoy, with the breakout success of rapper GloRilla’s Hitkidd-produced smash, “F.N.F. (Let’s Go).” McCoy says that being “fast and using the incredible amount of data we have today” has led the company to become an industry leader. “Taking ‘F.N.F.’ to No. 1 at [R&B/hip-hop] radio and being nominated for a Grammy after being told it was ‘regional’ highlighted a great year,” he says.

Todd Moscowitz

Founder/CEO, Alamo Records

Juliette Jones

COO, Alamo Records

Alamo Records superstar Lil Durk debuted at No. 3 on the Billboard 200 in June with Almost Healed after hitting No. 1 on the Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs chart with “All My Life” (featuring J. Cole) and No. 2 on the Hot 100. Alamo has also had significant growth over the past year thanks to the launch of its artist and label services company, Santa Anna, Jones says. She notes that Alamo’s focus with the division, led by president Lee L’Heureux, “is to partner with entrepreneurs in building their businesses,” citing team-ups with Conor Ambrose’s Listen to the Kids, Caroline “Baroline” Diaz’s Great Day and Laka Films’ No More Heroes and Now and Forever as “just the beginning.”

Brian Nolan

President of global marketing and sync, APG

Corey Calder

Senior vp of marketing and brand, APG

Eli Piccarreta

Vp of A&R, APG

APG scored a hit with the skillfully marketed Fast X soundtrack. After securing Jimin of BTS for a feature on Kodak Black and NLE Choppa’s “Angel Pt. 1” (Muni Long and JVKE are also featured), the album debuted atop the Soundtracks chart. The past year for APG has also included wins in artist development with Lambo4oe and Chase B, as well as Anti Da Menace, Sdot Go and Sweepers ENT, “who have an incredible movement breaking out of New York,” and Odetari, “who combines hip-hop and electronic music out of Houston,” says Nolan.

Mark Pitts

President, RCA Records; CEO, ByStorm Entertainment

Carolyn Williams

Executive vp, RCA Records

Sam Selolwane

Head of promotion (hip-hop, R&B, mixshow), RCA Records

George Clark III

Vp of marketing and A&R, RCA Records

Anthony “ADP” De Padua

Vp of digital marketing, RCA Records

Carlos Cuadros

Senior director of digital marketing, RCA Records

RCA has remained a dominant R&B/hip-hop player thanks to a powerful roster that includes Steve Lacy, SZA, Latto and Miguel. SZA’s highly anticipated SOS spent 10 weeks at No. 1 on the Billboard 200, while the single “Kill Bill” logged a record-breaking 21 weeks atop the Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs chart. Miguel’s single “Sure Thing,” resurrected by TikTok over a decade after its 2010 release, reached a new Hot 100 peak at No. 11 and broke the record for most weeks on Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs. Latto’s “Put It on Da Floor Again” with Cardi B reached No. 6 on Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs. Lacy won the best progressive R&B album Grammy for Gemini Rights, home to the Hot 100 No. 1 “Bad Habit.” Pitts says RCA is “looking toward the next wave of rising talent,” with Afrobeats signee Libianca already earning her first Hot 100 entry with the single “People.”

April Pope

Vp of label development and marketing, ADA Worldwide

Alassane Konaté

Director, ADA France

During the past 18 months, ADA Worldwide — the independent label and artist services division of Warner Music Group — has scored success on several fronts in R&B and hip-hop. The company made Mobb Deep rapper Prodigy’s solo catalog available on streaming services for the first time in three years. Plus, it distributed indie label Big.Ass.Kids’ compilation See You Next Year — a collaboration with new-music curator Pigeons & Planes and executive-produced by Grammy-winning engineer Mike Dean — and French rapper Menace Santana’s album Into the Dark. “ADA has fueled record-breaking results of emerging talents globally and been instrumental in pivotal cultural moments,” says Pope.

Ricky Reed

Founder/CEO, Nice Life Recording

Larry Wade

Co-owner/COO, Nice Life Recording

Nice Life’s profile rose with the globe-spanning success of Lizzo. Between scoring a No. 1 Hot 100 smash with “About Damn Time” and earning both a Grammy for record of the year and her first Adult R&B Airplay No. 1 with the SZA collaboration “Special,” Lizzo’s wins over the past 12 months have led to historic success for the label. But Wade says there’s plenty more in the works from Nice Life: “We’re very excited for what’s ahead, bolstered by new label signings, including Tinashe, and other developments within the company.”

Sylvia Rhone

Chairwoman/CEO, Epic Records

Ezekiel Lewis

President, Epic Records

Jennifer Goicoechea

Senior vp of A&R, Epic Records

Dontay Thompson

Senior vp of promotion, Epic Records

Chelsea Donnarumma

Vp of commercial partnerships, Epic Records

Justin Duran

Vp of marketing, Epic Records

Epic has a deep roster of R&B and hip-hop stars, including Travis Scott, 21 Savage, Real Boston Richey and Future, whose ninth album, I Never Liked You, topped the Billboard 200. “I have been lucky enough to work every Future album since Pluto and to be a part of so many No. 1s, including this one, his eighth, [which] will of course be a career highlight,” Donnarumma says. The Drake- and Tems-assisted single “Wait for U” debuted atop the Hot 100 in May 2022 to become Future’s first No. 1 as a lead artist and spent a record-breaking 16 weeks at No. 1 on the Mainstream R&B/Hip-Hop Airplay chart.

Jacqueline Saturn

President, Virgin Music

George Yarboi

Senior director of marketing, hip-hop and R&B, Virgin Music

Trenton Pratt

Director of streaming and playlisting ­strategy, hip-hop and R&B, Virgin Music

Virgin recently scored a major success with Nigerian artist Rema, whose single “Calm Down” with Selena Gomez hit No. 3 on the Hot 100 in June — a major feat for an African act. Elsewhere, rapper NF’s latest album, Hope, debuted at No. 2 on the Billboard 200 in April, marking his fourth consecutive top three entry on the chart. “We are lucky to work with the most incredible label partners on the planet and a Virgin team that has so much love and respect for one another,” Saturn says.

Snoop Dogg

Owner, Death Row Records

In February 2022, Snoop Dogg announced he had acquired Death Row Records — which released his 1993 multiplatinum debut, Doggystyle, and his follow-up albums — from MNRK Music Group. Then, in December, he sold a stake in the catalog to gamma, a new company led by former Apple Music executive Larry Jackson. “I’ve been in the game for more than two decades. I’m blessed,” Snoop says. “I’ve been able to do a lot in this game and in the recent past. I’m proud of bringing Death Row Records home. We’ve accomplished a lot since I took ownership, and it’s only going up from here.”

Steve Stoute

Founder/CEO, UnitedMasters

David Melhado

Vp of music and marketing, UnitedMasters

Mike Weiss

Vp of music/head of A&R, UnitedMasters

“This past year has been a huge growth year in building the artist partner business at UnitedMasters,” Weiss says. The rapper Superstar Pride climbed to No. 25 on the Hot 100 with the Faith Evans-sampling “Painting Pictures,” while BigXThaPlug’s AMAR spent four weeks atop the Heatseekers Albums chart and Tobe Nwigwe earned a best new artist Grammy nomination. In May, independent R&B star Brent Faiyaz, who has over 1 billion on-demand streams so far this year, announced that he had partnered with UnitedMasters as well. Taken together, Melhado says, these wins indicate that UnitedMasters is “well positioned to support artists at every phase of their journey.”

Abou “Bu” Thiam

Executive vp of A&R, Columbia Records

Wilt Wallace

Senior vp of urban promotion, Columbia Records

Lisa Wiggins

Vp of artist relations and touring, Columbia Records

Victoria White-Mason

Vp of marketing, Columbia Records

Chika Ifediora

Manager of digital marketing, Columbia Records

Touré Shiver

Director of digital marketing, Columbia Records

Columbia Records has gained acclaim “through our ability to launch the careers of top new R&B artists like Chlöe and Q,” Shiver says, “and to expand the legacies of icons like Tyler, The Creator and Pharrell [Williams] with large-scale campaigns and creative content that excites fans globally.” Columbia also had other success stories over the past year, including Beyoncé’s long-anticipated return with her Billboard 200 No. 1-debuting Renaissance and the continued presence on the chart of Lil Nas X’s Montero, Fivio Foreign’s B.I.B.L.E. and Polo G’s first No. 1 album, Hall of Fame.

Pierre “P” Thomas

CEO, Quality Control

Kevin “Coach K” Lee

COO, Quality Control

Simone Mitchell

President, Quality Control

Brandra Ringo

Executive vp/co-head of A&R, Quality Control

Quality Control is celebrating its 10th anniversary this year and is “so thankful to be one of the biggest rap labels in the game,” Mitchell says. QC’s standout accomplishments from the past year include its merger with HYBE; the release of Lil Baby’s third album, It’s Only Me, and the Prime Video documentary Untrapped: The Story of Lil Baby; the release of Lil Yachty’s psychedelic rock album, Let’s Start Here; the launch of Yung Miami’s REVOLT talk show, Caresha Please; and the development of newer acts like Duke Deuce, Lakeyah and Gloss Up. “There’s too much to name,” Mitchell adds, “but it’s always about staying on track with discovering what is out there and growing what we have.”

Thomas has also been named Billboard ’s first R&B/Hip-Hop Power Players’ Choice Award recipient. Read more here.

Anthony “Top Dawg” Tiffith

CEO, Top Dawg Entertainment

Anthony “Moosa” Tiffith

Terrence “Punch” Henderson

Co-presidents, Top Dawg Entertainment

The past year has proved to be a rewarding one for Top Dawg Entertainment, as SZA’s record-breaking run with her second studio album — SOS, released in partnership with RCA — further pushed her into the stratosphere. The single “Kill Bill” hit No. 1 on the Hot 100 — a first for the superstar — while the album spent 10 weeks at No. 1. “It has been great watching SZA’s SOS dominate and break as many records as [it] has,” Anthony “Top Dawg” Tiffith says, “and then to take the show on the road for the world tour only further solidifies her as a generational talent.” Other wins for the label include the return of Ab-Soul with the album Herbert and Doechii breaking through with her single “What It Is (Block Boy)” (featuring Kodak Black), which hit No. 1 on Rhythmic Airplay.

Andre Torres

Senior vp of global catalog development and marketing, recorded music, Warner Music Group

The Warner Music Group team has spent the year celebrating hip-hop’s 50th anniversary, “encompassing live events, vinyl releases, [merchandise] and bespoke playlists,” Torres says. These projects include new vinyl from Wiz Khalifa, Kevin Gates, Wale and Sean Paul. As part of the label’s hip-hop campaign, Young Thug’s colored-vinyl exclusives for Jeffery (first released in 2016) and Beautiful Thugger Girls (2017) arrived in partnership with Vinyl Me, Please and sold out on their respective release dates.

Steven Victor

CEO, Victor Victor Worldwide; Librero/UMG

Earlier this year, Victor watched Pusha T land another Grammy nomination for his Billboard 200 No. 1 album, It’s Almost Dry. At the same time, his other client, The-Dream, racked up accolades for his contributions to Beyoncé’s 2022 album, Renaissance, including a best dance/electronic album award at the Grammys in February. As Victor Victor Worldwide continues to enjoy wins on the music side, the company recently branched out into sports and now manages reigning boxing champ Gervonta “Tank” Davis, who scored a significant victory against Ryan Garcia in April.

Bryan “Birdman” Williams

Ronald “Slim” Williams

Co-founders/co-CEOs, Cash Money Records

Thanks to their work with artists including Lil Wayne, Nicki Minaj and Drake (who scored his 11th and 12th Billboard 200 No. 1 albums with Honestly, Nevermind and Her Loss in 2022), the Williams brothers were honored with the Living Legends Foundation’s lifetime achievement award in October on the organization’s 30th anniversary. Beyond championing hip-hop heavyweights, Cash Money Records also successfully launched a number of emerging artists this year, including Eighty8, Onsight Deeda, Rublow and Saxkboy KD.

Nicole Wyskoarko

President of A&R, Interscope Geffen A&M

Aaron “Dash” Sherrod

President of A&R, Geffen

Tim Glover

Executive vp of A&R, Interscope

Laura Carter

Executive vp/head of urban marketing, Interscope

Ramon Alvarez-Smikle

Executive vp/head of digital marketing, Interscope

Keinon Johnson

Executive vp of urban radio promotions, Interscope

The label group has chalked up several wins for Collective Music Group artists GloRilla, Moneybagg Yo and EST Gee, Dreamville’s Ari Lennox and J.I.D, and LVRN’s Summer Walker alongside Kendrick Lamar’s fifth album and world tour. Interscope also celebrated the 30th anniversary of The Chronic, which, Carter says, “returned Dr. Dre’s magnum opus home to its original distribution partner,” Interscope. She says that warming up in the wings is Playboi Carti’s Opium label and its artists, “including Destroy Lonely, another major breakout for 2023, and Ken Carson, with highly anticipated new music on the way.”

Andre “Dr. Dre” Young

Founder/CEO, Aftermath Entertainment

Ashley Palmer-Gilkey

GM, Aftermath Entertainment

In February, Dr. Dre announced that his landmark solo debut album, The Chronic, had returned to original distributor Interscope and would receive a special rerelease for its 30th anniversary. At the same time, it was revealed that the album would again be available on streaming services; it had been pulled following Snoop Dogg’s 2022 purchase of the Death Row label, which first released The Chronic in 1992. “We’re thrilled by the album’s enduring popularity with people all over the world,” Palmer-Gilkey says, “and are working on a variety of unique offerings for fans that we’re excited about.”

Tunde Balogun

Co-founder/president, LVRN

Junia Abaidoo

Co-founder/head of operations and touring, LVRN

Justice Baiden

Co-founder/head of A&R, LVRN

Sean “Famoso” McNichol

Co-founder/head of marketing and brand ­partnerships, LVRN

Carlon Ramong

Co-founder/creative director, LVRN

Amber Grimes

Executive vp/GM, LVRN

LVRN’s management side has continued to raise the bar with its clients’ success stories, beginning with Davido’s fourth studio album, Timeless, which peaked at No. 2 on the World Albums chart. Baby Tate also scored a victory with her viral hit, “Hey Mickey!,” which appeared on multiple charts, including Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs and Hot Rap Songs. Tate’s TikTok triumph earned a boost when “Hey Mickey!” received a remix with Saweetie. This year, LVRN’s flagship artists Summer Walker and 6LACK also returned with new projects, most notably Clear 2: Soft Life EP and Since I Have a Lover, respectively.

Peter Bittenbender

CEO, Mass Appeal

From immersive events and photo exhibits in New York to Swizz Beatz’s Hip Hop 50: Vol. 2 album, Mass Appeal is a driving force in creating experiences that celebrate a half century of hip-hop. Those efforts will culminate with an Aug. 11 concert at Yankee Stadium boasting a cross-generational lineup of rap luminaries. “Our team has been working tirelessly to commemorate hip-hop’s undeniable global impact on our culture,” Bittenbender says. “We’re incredibly appreciative of our co-producers, Live Nation and the New York Yankees, for making this legendary concert possible and giving hip-hop the 50th birthday celebration it deserves.”

Shawn “Jay-Z” Carter

Founder/chairman, Roc Nation

Desiree Perez

CEO, Roc Nation

Jay Brown

Vice chairman, Roc Nation

The story of the year for Roc Nation was the return of Rihanna, who not only wowed at the most watched Super Bowl halftime show in history (executive-produced by Roc Nation), complete with a pregnancy reveal, but landed an Academy Award nomination for “Lift Me Up” from the Black Panther: Wakanda Forever soundtrack. Also, company client Lil Uzi Vert landed his seventh Hot 100 top 10 with “Just Wanna Rock,” while Ambré scored her first No. 1 on a Billboard chart with the Adult R&B Airplay hit “I’m Baby” (featuring Jvck James), another of Roc Nation’s “multiple milestones and groundbreaking achievements,” says Perez.

Karen Civil

Executive vp/GM, Lil Wayne/Young Money Records

In December, Lil Wayne earned his first RIAA diamond certification for “Lollipop” (featuring Static Major) after the 2008 single made a resurgence on TikTok. The New Orleans rapper also performed 30 intimate shows on the Welcome to Tha Carter Tour with special guests Drake, Chance the Rapper, Cam’ron, 2 Chainz and more. Among a series of wins for her top client, Civil remains most proud of Lil Wayne receiving the Global Impact Award from the Recording Academy’s Black Music Collective in February. “The honor highlighted Wayne’s massive impact on the music industry as he continues to discover global superstars,” she says, referring to the rapper’s co-signs on artists including Drake, Nicki Minaj and Tyga.
